tldr: The user wanted to add a database, an admin dashboard, and authentication
  to their sleep questionnaire application. The project involved implementing a
  PostgreSQL database with Prisma, building a simple password-protected admin
  dashboard with CSV export, and setting up Next.js middleware for
  authentication.
overview: The user initiated a project to enhance their sleep questionnaire
  application by integrating a database for response storage, developing an
  admin dashboard for data access, and implementing an authentication system.
  The approach involved using Prisma with NeonDB (PostgreSQL) for the database,
  creating a  model to store both raw and denormalized
  demographic data. For the admin dashboard, a login page and a table view of
  responses with CSV export functionality were built. Initially, a custom
  session management system was implemented, but this was later refined to
  leverage Next.js middleware for simpler and more efficient route protection
  and authentication using a basic cookie. The demographic data collected was
  aligned with the SOW, including year of birth, sex, zipcode, weight, and
  height. During the testing phase, it was identified that the "Pre-fill & Jump
  to Report" feature did not trigger a database save, which was then
  successfully verified through a direct API call. The final outcome is a fully
  functional database, an authenticated admin dashboard, and a streamlined
  authentication system.
